  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "The pod status manager, when fails to update, [deletes the cached value to trigger the next update](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/165169ab1c18f0a6df60505a1bdc7783e56b303e/pkg/kubelet/status/manager.go#L262). This is not preferable because for the following reasons:\n-  kubelet has grown organically to rely on the statuses in this cache. E.g., `git grep -n statusManager.GetPodStatus` shows\n\n```\nkubelet.go:1353:                        existingStatus, ok := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(podToUpdate.UID)\nkubelet.go:1450:                        status, found := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(pod.UID)\nkubelet.go:1573:                status, found := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(pod.UID)\nkubelet.go:1660:                podStatus, ok := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(pod.UID)\nkubelet.go:1680:        status, ok := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(pod.UID)\nkubelet.go:2218:        podStatus, found := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(podUID)\nkubelet.go:2695:        if existingStatus, hasExistingStatus := kl.statusManager.GetPodStatus(pod.UID); hasExistingStatus {\n```\n\nArbitrarily deleting the values may affect access to such data from other components.\n- This mechanism assumes kubelet would write pod status update periodically. This may no longer be true once we switch to the event-driven model (#12802), or at the least, the period would be much longer.\n\nI suggest instruct status manager to use a different mechanism to requeue the update. Thoughts? @kubernetes/goog-node \n",
